<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-316-249  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 316 249.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEE Proceedings Part E Computers and Digital Techniques  January1989 v136 n1 p1(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Changes of light. (optoelectronic communications) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horne, N.W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The paper is concerned with the technology of optoelectroniccommunications.andP;  It describes the basic technology and the effectof very high speed connectivity on the design and use ofcommunications and information systems.andP;  Developments in thesesystems can be characterised into three revolutions: hardware,software and communications.andP;  The hardware revolution started withthe invention of the electronic valve, continued with thetransistor, and has permeated our daily lives in the form of theintegrated circuit.andP;  The software revolution started later withthe invention of languages and sophisticated operating systems,greatly increasing the ability to produce complex systems quickly.andO;The communications revolution is in its early stages; it is basedon optoelectronic technology.andP;  The paper describes thefundamentals of transmitting light through optical fibre includingthe evolution from low capacity systems to the latest ideas onmultichannel high capacity techniques.andP;  Optoelectronicstransmission technology evolved in response to the demands oftelecommunications, and it has been widely applied in highcapacity routes over recent years.andP;  The technology affecting thearchitecture and design of complex systems, such as mainframecomputers and digital telephone exchanges, is illustrated for thehardware and for the software of such systems.andP;  The conclusion isthat the changes being caused by the use of light as a connectingtechnique represent the third revolution in informationtechnology.andP;  Furthermore, these changes are magnifying andaccelerating the effects of the two earlier revolutions ofhardware and software technologies.andP;  The full extent of thechanges being caused by light are only just becoming apparent.andO;(Reprinted by permission of the publisher)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optoelectronic DevicesCommunications TechnologyTechnologyState-of-the-ArtOutlookHistoryFiber OpticsOptical CommunicationsOptical Computers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphchart.andO;Caption:   DRAM single-chip memory size development. (graph)Light transmission through optical fibres. (chart)Programming productivity development. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>